# Backend Conventions

## Services

- Google API logic lives in `backend/src/services/*`, each extending `WorkspaceService`.
- Access clients via `this.admin` / `this.drive` / `this.gmail` / `this.calendar` after `await this.initialize(userEmail)` — this builds a **keyless** DWD client for `userEmail` (a minted per-user access token; no key file, no mutable `.subject`). To act as a different user, call `initialize()` again with that email.
- Wrap Google calls in `this.withRetry(() => client.x.y(...))` (handles 429/5xx backoff and status extraction). It returns `any` by design; narrow the result at the call site (e.g. `response.data as DirectoryUser`).
- For bulk per-item Google calls, use `mapWithConcurrency(items, limit, worker)` from `utils/concurrency.ts` — never fire thousands of unbounded parallel requests.

## Routes

- Routes are thin: authenticate, gate permissions, validate/normalize input, call a service, respond.
- Middleware order: `authenticateSession` → `requireAnyAdmin` | `requireSuperAdmin` | `requirePermission(...)` → `auditLog(...)` for mutations.
- Normalize email path params with `normalizeEmailParam` (`utils/email.ts`). CSV exports use `convertToCSV` + `generateExportFilename` (`utils/csv.ts`).

## Error handling

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
} catch (error: any) {
  res.status(error.status || 500).json({ error: error.message });
}

// ✅ GOOD — resolves true Google status + actionable hint, logs server-side
} catch (error: any) {
  sendApiError(res, error, 'Failed to list delegations', 'gmail.delegations.get');
}
```

- Do not add `@ts-nocheck`. Do not swallow errors silently in single-item operations (propagate); tolerate-and-log only in bulk scans.
